export const VOLUMES = {"I":{"title":"Raw concrete, board-marked and weathered","intro":"Brutalism is a palette of béton brut — raw concrete — in its many weathers: fresh grey, rain-streaked, board-marked, and warmed by the timber and carpet of its interiors. The colour is monolithic, tonal, and textural. Each refuses the cold dead-grey caricature: real brutalist concrete is warm, varied, and full of the grain of its formwork."},"II":{"title":"The Jazz-Age skyline, chrome, terracotta, and pastel","intro":"Art Deco runs from Manhattan's chrome-and-stone towers to the pastel stucco of Miami Beach — geometric, luxurious, and colour-confident, with metal, glazed terracotta, and bold trim. The palettes are glamorous and varied by region. Each refuses the beige 'old building' assumption: Deco is chrome, jade, coral, and gold by design."},"III":{"title":"The great churches, stone, glass, and coloured light","intro":"The Gothic cathedral is grey stone transformed by coloured light — the deep blues and reds of stained glass thrown across pale limestone, candle gold, and the dark of the vaults. The palette is cool stone lit by jewelled fire. Each refuses the flat 'grey church' assumption: the cathedral's whole purpose is stone dissolved in coloured light."},"IV":{"title":"The Japanese house, wood, paper, and tatami","intro":"Traditional Japanese architecture is a palette of natural materials in restraint: cedar and cypress wood, paper screens, tatami straw, clay plaster, and the dark of lacquer and tile. The colour is warm, muted, and tuned to filtered light. Each refuses the red-lacquer-temple cliché: most Japanese building is quiet wood, paper, and earth, with red reserved for shrines."},"V":{"title":"The sun-built south, lime, earth, and shade","intro":"Mediterranean vernacular building uses local lime, earth, and stone against hard sun — whitewash, terracotta, ochre, and the deep blue of shutter and dome. The palette is bright, warm, and made for heat. Each refuses the single 'Santorini blue-and-white' shorthand: each region has its own earth, lime, and shutter colour."},"VI":{"title":"The modern movement, white walls and primary accents","intro":"Modernism stripped ornament to white render, glass, and steel — with the Bauhaus and De Stijl adding disciplined primary accents. The palette is clean, light, and precise, with colour used as deliberate punctuation. Each refuses the all-white sterility: modernism uses white as a ground for primary red, blue, and yellow, plus natural stone and wood."},"VII":{"title":"The Islamic world, tile, light, and geometry","intro":"Islamic architecture turns surface into colour — glazed tile in turquoise and cobalt, carved stucco, honey stone, and the play of filtered light through screens. The palettes are luminous, geometric, and tile-rich. Each refuses a flat 'desert sand' assumption: the great monuments are jewelled with turquoise, cobalt, and gold."},"VIII":{"title":"The north, pale wood, falu red, and soft light","intro":"Nordic architecture works with pale birch and pine, white plaster, the deep falu-red of farm timber, and turf, all under low northern light. The palette is warm-natural and quiet, tuned to long winters. Each refuses cold minimalist grey: the Nordic palette is warm pale wood and falu red, not a sterile white box."},"IX":{"title":"The American grain, adobe, clapboard, and brick","intro":"American vernacular building is regional and material-led: Southwestern adobe, New England clapboard, prairie brick-and-oak, and the painted ladies of the West Coast. The palette shifts with local earth and weather. Each refuses a single 'farmhouse' look: each region's vernacular has its own earth, paint, and timber colour."},"X":{"title":"The revolutionary state, concrete, red, and marble","intro":"Soviet and Constructivist architecture runs from the bold red-and-grey of the avant-garde to the marble-and-bronze opulence of the Moscow Metro and the raw concrete of late monuments. The palette is industrial, with propaganda red and gilt. Each refuses a flat 'grey communist' look: from metro marble to mosaic, this is a surprisingly rich and varied tradition."},"XI":{"title":"The playful turn, colour, curve, and quotation","intro":"Postmodern and expressionist architecture brought colour and gesture back — pastel classical quotation, titanium curves, and sculptural white. The palettes are bold, witty, and material-distinctive. Each refuses the sober modernist neutral: these buildings use colour and sheen as statement."},"XII":{"title":"The working buildings, brick, iron, and glass","intro":"Industrial architecture is brick, cast iron, steel, and big glass — the colour of mills, power stations, and warehouses, weathered by work and soot. The palette is robust, warm-brick or grey-steel, with rust and patina. Each refuses a sanitised loft-conversion gloss: real industrial colour is sooty brick, oxidised iron, and grimy glass."}};
